Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law on the introduction of administrative liability for violation of the term and procedure for payment for goods (works, services) when making purchases for state and municipal needs.
This law is designed to solve a very acute problem of non-fulfillment of their obligations by customers in the implementation of state and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation when entrepreneurs could not receive payment under already executed state and municipal contracts was ubiquitous.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Prosecutor General's Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who concluded contracts that were not supported by financing, tried in every possible way to evade their payment obligations and included illegal conditions in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in the interests of protecting the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, the prosecutor's office has made 9.7 thousand submissions, as a result of their consideration, 4.5 thousand officials were brought to disciplinary responsibility, 533 to administrative liability, 75 materials were submitted to the investigative bodies for the organization of procedural checks, criminal cases were initiated on 46 of them.
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles was repaid.
Moreover, these huge sums were not accumulated as a result of non-payment of multibillion-dollar contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in paying services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts led to fabulous debts.
Here's a typical case.
The head of a small company won a tender for the provision of social transportation services for several million rubles.
The person invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is a growing financial lump of debts on salaries, taxes, loans, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not turned to the prosecutor's office for help.
Now in a number of regions the problem has been leveled as much as possible.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts identified by prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical values, the prosecutor's office works in the mode of manual crisis management.
The Prosecutor General personally holds field meetings with representatives of local authorities, at which all violations discovered by prosecutors and measures for their immediate elimination are thoroughly examined.
Such operational meetings have already been held this year in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg.
The implementation of Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On Amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offenses regarding the Establishment of Administrative Responsibility of Customer Officials for Violation of the Deadline and Procedure for Payment for Goods (Works, Services) when Making Purchases to Meet State and Municipal Needs", which was signed by the President of Russia last week, will be able to qualitatively improve the payment discipline of public customers.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia at the initiative of the Prosecutor General's Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offenses with an article that provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by an official of the customer of the term and procedure for payment for goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
And if an official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offense, then he will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative innovations in practice.
Civil Rights Group Announces Missouri Travel Warning
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People Traveler Warning, valid through August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors, and Missouri citizens to be especially careful and extra cautious when traveling within the state due to a number of questionable racist incidents that have recently occurred throughout the state and are brought here."
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the group's travel warning was prompted by a recent Missouri law that made it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as the fact that state law enforcement agencies disproportionately target minorities.
"You have people who are subject to human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of their skin color, beaten and killed," Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, told the Kansas City Star.
"We hear complaints more often than ever before."
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization to a U.S. state.
The group cited incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of twenty-eight-year-old Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas while touring the state and Missouri state police arrested him without charging him with a crime.
The warning also mentions a recent missouri attorney general's office report that black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
"The purpose of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to alert their family and friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
"People need to be prepared in one way or another, whether they will take money with them for bail or tell relatives that they are traveling around the state."
According to the latest data from the FBI's Hate Crimes Reporting Program, Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, making the state the sixteenth most such offenses in the state.
Also, the travel warning is a response to a new Missouri law, after which it will be more difficult to bring a case against a legal entity for housing or labor discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued warnings for travelers to Texas and Arizona after these states passed new immigration control laws that required local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which, according to the ACLU, should have increased the number of checks on racial grounds.
Travel alerts are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently community organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
