Disneyland with the death penalty.
Why do Singapore comply with the law?
I'm talking to a local businessman, Chang, while sitting in an outdoor diner.
Commenting on the situation in Singapore, Chang smokes one cigarette after another, while he carefully stores cigarette butts in an iron box taken with him from the office.
After the end of the conversation, the businessman goes to the nearest urn - a hundred meters to it - and throws the gobies there.
The fine for garbage in a public place is $500, Chang said.
You know, since childhood, I just developed a reflex: you can not throw a candy wrapper on the pavement, they will instantly fine.
And now there are video cameras everywhere.
And indeed - the sidewalks of Singapore in the city center are clean, like in a museum.
Chang says three months ago, his neighbor's 18-year-old son painted graffiti on the wall of an old colonial building.
The court found the guy guilty of vandalism and sentenced him to flogging.
What?!
Imagine.
He received ten blows to the buttocks with a wooden stick and spent a week in jail.
Corporal punishment is not uncommon in our country.
How Singapore combines the highest standard of living and incredibly harsh laws, the AiF columnist understood on the spot.
No one here thinks about abolishing the death penalty," explains lawyer Victor Lee Hong.
And the government has long cared about the opinion of both the European Union and the United States on this matter.
If a person carries a large consignment of drugs or sells them, he is entitled to the gallows.
In 2002, a 22-year-old Australian citizen was detained at Changi airport carrying 400 grams of cocaine.
The Australian Prime Minister spoke in his defense, threatening sanctions, international human rights activists and even the Pope.
However, the guy was eventually hanged anyway.
After that, drug couriers diligently bypass our country.
The fact is this: in Singapore, it is supposed that the laws are obliged to comply with EVERYTHING in a row, and not just modest and poor people.
It does not matter who you are - a millionaire, a deputy prime minister, a famous artist or a resident of the European Union.
There is only one option in this case: if they find half a kilo of cocaine in your possession, you will be hanged.
When you walk around Singapore and everywhere you meet signs with a bunch of warnings, you simply wonder - how many bans there are in this city-state!
For example, chewing gum is sold only in pharmacies, and you can buy it strictly by prescription (!) of a doctor.
Upon arrival, chewing gum will not be taken away from a tourist, but it is worth gluing a "rubber band" in the subway, a fine of 1 thousand local dollars will be imposed.
Over four days, I met two people with white signs around their necks: "I littered."
For throwing a cigarette butt past the urn, in addition to a fine, they are often sentenced to "exile to the janitors": a week to clean parks and beaches.
6 thousand rubles. pays a "criminal" who forgot to wash off the water in a public toilet, and when trying to cope with a small need in the elevator of an apartment building, a special detector is triggered - the doors are blocked and a signal is sent to the police.
Among the most exotic laws are prohibitions on feeding pigeons on the street, public performance of songs and even excessive watering of indoor plants (!): it is believed that the abundance of water attracts mosquitoes.
To avoid fires, smokers should not bring lighters into the subway, otherwise they will be fined 5 thousand Singapore bucks.
In general, there is a thought: no matter how hard you try, you will definitely break something.
This is not the case at all," Mohammed Kabir-Qajariya, the owner of a local travel agency, tries to dissuade me.
Particularly fantastic laws exist only on paper, and in the last twenty years I have not seen anyone prosecuted for violating them.
Why are they preserved?
So that citizens do not relax.
Compliance with the basic rules is strictly monitored.
For example, if a minor is sold cigarettes in a kiosk, then everything will be punished along the chain: the owner of the store will pay a huge amount, the offender himself will receive blows with sticks on the "back", and the seller will also be whipped and put in prison.
It is thanks to such harsh laws that offenses in Singapore are very rare.
Is this justified?
Back in the seventies, we had chaos on the roads - motorists ignored traffic lights, drove as they wanted, got drunk behind the wheel.
After the introduction of fines for the year, everything calmed down.
Now the driver, having drunk a portion of whiskey, knows: if they stop, the policeman will not let him go for a bribe, they will impose a fine in the amount of the cost of the apartment and will be sent to jail for years.
To many foreigners, the city-state in Southeast Asia seems like a kind of concentration camp.
In 1993, the American writer William Gibson called Singapore "Disneyland with the death penalty" - the guest from the United States was horrified by the general wealth of the inhabitants, the "frighteningly clean airport" and the "cultivated nature".
They say that such things are unnatural, they look artificial, and this should not be the case in principle.
The first days in Singapore and rightly afraid to throw a piece of paper on the sidewalk, you wake up if you go to the subway with ice cream.
But then you arrive in the "Little India" area, and suddenly - "breaking the pattern": plastic cups are lying around at the bus stop.
"How's that?" you wonder.
And like this," Singaporeans chuckle.
Things do happen.
Not every such "crime" will be captured on the spot, but you should know that if you are calculated, you will not be punished - because you broke the law.
Most often, this is enough for a person to behave normally.
Of course, the government in Singapore is quite authoritarian.
But you know what?
In Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam, I moved very carefully - motorcyclists often snatch smartphones and cameras from the hands of tourists.
The center of Paris is full of dirty bums and beggars.
On our streets, too, not everyone tries to throw garbage in the bins.
Singapore, thanks to a set of draconian fines and ruthless (up to the death penalty) laws, has become the calmest, cleanest and safest city on Earth.
Come to think of it.
This is human nature: remember, and in Russia no one buckled up behind the wheel until they began to fine.
Although the main thing in Singapore is not fines, but voluntary compliance with the laws.
And we must think that here in Russia people would also be happy with clean streets, the absence of garbage in the subway and would welcome the arrest of those who confuse the elevator with a public toilet.
Here's corporal punishment - thank you, don't.
Otherwise, the laws of Singapore are at least worth taking a closer look at.
Nothing sacred?
Now the Trump White House is targeting the Statue of Liberty.
The surest sign of regime change is when it starts fighting statues.
Americans understand this as well as anyone else – hence the deliberate theatrical demolition of the statue of Saddam Hussein in Baghdad's Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the Key Ideologues of the Trump administration, no doubt knew what he was doing when he brought the symbolic axe over the Statue of Liberty during a bitter dispute with CNN journalist Jim Acosta about the president's proposals to drastically reduce legal migration.
Let's be honest, Miller didn't attempt on the statue itself.
Hordes of pleasure boat owners and artists depicting the Statue of Liberty would have lynched him if he had tried.
But he encroached on its meaning, and especially on the meaning that was attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument, when the poems of Emma Lazarus were added to the pedestal.
As Miller grumbled at Acosta, "I don't want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you are talking about was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller got the facts right, but as he said, it's not really about history.
It's about the current sound of the astounding words of Lazarus, the only ones in which the state invites not all immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / Your crowds dreaming of breathing freely, / The wretched dregs of your bountiful shores."
Never before have the "unfortunate scum" been so visible on our screens.
Miller was not engaged in literary criticism - he made it clear that in America Trump these people are not expected.
This debate over the statue's meaning is part of a broader political and cultural war: it's really a dispute about the meaning of America.
Lazarus – and her friends, who fought to put her words on the plinth of the statue after her death – understood very well that they were committing a completely political act.
The sculpture was intended to mark the connection between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classical figure - the female image of Freedom.
Lazarus changed her meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a very different name: Mother of the Exiled.
The combination of poem and image was a brilliant feminist move and a crushing attack against American nativism.
And as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right though changed it back.
The vociferous Rush Limbaugh, a kind of John the Baptist who heralded the coming of Trump, reasoned in 2010 that Freedom does not invite anyone, rather it is an early neoconservative, bringing the flame of America to the world lying in darkness: "Freedom is moving forward.
It carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to light the way to the United States."
Against usual, Limbaugh really hit the nail on the head here.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
Lazarus's great creative achievement was to see her as she would have been seen by exhausted, miserable, but hopeful people on the decks of ships after a long and often arduous voyage.
It means literally looking at the world through the eyes of people who are seeking asylum and a chance at a better life.
Her statue responds to them with the words of hope and hospitality they dream of hearing.
And, of course, this is not a prospect that Miller and Trump will ever want to recognize.
Their torch is needed not to light the way, but to incite hatred, which is the only source of their strength.
