Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you're not willing to listen to criticism from voters
The founder of our country understood what a critical press was.
Americans loved George Washington, but that didn't stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
The criticism of him, of course, irritated him.
But he didn't silence his critics.
Because back in 1783, Washington said, "You can take away freedom of speech and we, deaf and dumb, will be led like sheep to the slaughterhouse."
Now I'll move on to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should have tried to be more like Washington.
Hogan's subordinates blocked and erased the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subordinates called this lawsuit null and void, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of "so what."
"It's just Facebook," many will say.
But it's also important.
And that's especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is a remarkably popular Republican governor in a predominantly Democratic state.
He is in second place in the approval rating among the 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He has demonstrated a firm hand in managing the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also deftly uses Facebook as the primary way to communicate with his constituents and jokingly displays his bald head after chemotherapy on his page.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor's page - which is declared as an official public forum and is conducted by administration officials with taxpayers' money - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with the Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Ches defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking comments is simply moderating them.
But it's all too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters spitting on the internet.
The Post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are real people, not trolls, a teacher, a businessman, a pastor who appeal to their elected leaders.
They all say their comments were respectful, meaningful and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing that Hogan was Catholic.
Lakshmi's lawyer, Sarma Ramana of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred but asked about hate crimes.
"I wrote a polite comment saying that I am disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news," she wrote in the comments section of the post article.
"I also don't like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it's so-called cheating, instead of admitting that they are dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens."
What the governor's subordinates call a "concentrated spam attack," others would probably call an "active life position."
In the Facebook era, it's easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
It's a much less dusty job than before, when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical editorials, or arresting and silencing protesters.
But this is exactly what is happening now, only in digital.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social networks.
President Trump was sued by Twitter users who were banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James C. Casheris of alexandria, the chairman of the County Supervisory Board of Loudon violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from her Facecbook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington's time, the era of affordable postage made about the same upheaval as the Internet is today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters greatly undermined his authority.
And even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms "Yurikola", "Valerius", "Belizearius" and "Porcius" wrote letters to newspapers ridiculing Washington's decision.
According to historical documents collected by the online project "George Washington Papers", his cabinet was littered with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Amity, Commerce and Navigation.
But he didn't try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lies at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing to that.
