Poverty and death in Indonesia's "golden land"
When cooking dinner, Bardina Degeia does not use the stove.
She rarely uses the potty.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually simply places sweet potatoes, which here are called "note", directly into the hearth.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is taken out and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degeia sits on an earthen floor – she has no furniture – and this is where she does her chores around the house, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The restroom serves as a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, and so she was not assigned to work in the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men from this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
"No one dares to walk around the village after five in the evening," she says.
It's a rare opportunity to look at daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by publicly raising their hands in front of occupying troops.
The existing pro-independence movement from the Netherlands quickly turned its ire against the Jakarta government, which retains tight control over the region by keeping foreign journalists and human rights defenders out.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes an hour and a half flight from Jayapura, the provincial capital, to Nabir, and then a five-hour shake in a hired car.
There is no public transport here.
The city of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; corrugated steel roofs are painted with rust in a variety of reddish shades.
Few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and almost none of the foreigners got here.
Prior to the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuans worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes.
"It was unusual for us to wear these clothes," Degei says, pointing to his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
"We used to wear only leaves on our bodies."
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it's also indonesian golden land.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a highland province roughly the size of New Jersey, home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves valued at $78 billion.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful armed forces maintain their suffocating presence here.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
Demands for greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this gold mine and are ruthlessly suppressed.
Since 1969, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned, human rights activists say.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, massacres in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the seventies can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3900 peaceful protesters in the region.
"We will lose everything," a report published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as summary executions, torture – particularly frequent, as another report claims, rape and electrocution – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because the incidents take place every week," Andreas Harrisono, who does research in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The hype tightened as Papua's resources attracted an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's 3.5-million population is 83% Christian, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese shops, "varungi", sell fried chicken and a mixture of vegetables "gado-gado" served with peanut sauce.
Local residents are trying to withstand competition.
"Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables cheaper in the traditional market than the indigenous people of Papua," explains Abet Yow, a twenty-four-year-old native of Paniai who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, because of her work.
"Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua – Papua's mama-mama (women) – have lost their market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, vowed to address inequality and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Paniai.
But in Papua, almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, expecting him to fulfill our hopes for justice," says Yow.
In fact, just two months after Jokowi's inauguration in October, Paniai survived the tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were on the street singing Christmas carols around a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle emerged from the darkness.
The frightened children told them they should turn on their headlights.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and returned with four soldiers after a while.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, soldiers who were drunk chased after children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julianus Eimo, was so badly beaten that he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone set fire to the nearby government election commission building, and the next day the situation escalated.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought ritual hunting bows with them and performed vaita, a dance of the Papuan mee pago tribe: they ran in circles and depicted bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and military base.
As the situation escalated, the soldiers were given an internal radio order: "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them," according to an official document seen by TIME magazine but not published in local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Eremias Kayame, the head of the Kego Koto district in Enarotali, sensed the approach of danger and called for calm, asking the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen to him.
"When I turned, I was suddenly hit in the left wrist by a bullet," he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayama still does not know who fired the shots, but says the bullet came from a line of assembled soldiers.
"There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots," he adds.
Local resident Alfius Jove was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," Yohanes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told TIME magazine grimly.
"I saw that he was dead ... I kissed him."
Gen. Yotje Mende, a senior police inspector in Papua, told reporters that his officers were only "defending" their base because it was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," Papua police spokesman Commissioner Pujo Sulistillo said in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the killings didn't reach Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi delivered a passionate speech in Jayapura in which he expressed condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the issue of historical abuses of power in Papua.
"I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future," he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Wiranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to end historical human rights abuses.
But almost immediately there were excuses.
"Most of the violations occurred a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or early noughties.
The fact is that we certainly want to address these violations, but there are procedures that need to be gone through," he said.
Wiranto then retracted his remarks, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he had no plans to establish an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, "Everything will be decided through the courts."
Wiranto, who was accused by the United Nations of "crimes against humanity" over the deaths of more than 1,000 people during the bloody east Timorese independence vote in 1999, said 11 cases of human rights abuses in Papua had already been settled, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims from Paniai met such statements with grim disbelief.
"I've been questioned four times in the last three years, but there has been absolutely no change," Says Johannes.
"I'm tired."
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
"I'm scared," he says.
"I'm afraid I'm going to be arrested by the military, I'm afraid I'm going to get shot."
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the residents of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
"After we buried the bodies, the military came for me," he says.
The shooting did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot at villagers in the neighboring Deiyai district of Paniai.
In a clash between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to help take an unconscious man to the hospital, one person was killed and 17 others were injured, including children.
A man, twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Dove, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the office of a construction site owned by the company.
According to police, the villagers threw stones at the officers, who fired warning shots in response.
But locals claim that a mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) fired on the crowd and killed one person.
"We've been in such a panic, we're afraid of retaliation," twenty-nine-year-old Domingu Badii, who lives near the hospital and hastily seen the wounded rushed in, told TIME magazine.
"I hid at home for two days."
Parliament Deiyai demanded that the officers involved in the incident be held accountable and the mobile police brigade withdrawn from the region.
Paniyai has always been a sore spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development angers the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes scattered throughout the green-covered central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Movement for a Free Papua (OPM), a rebel army that claims to protect the rights of Papuans by staging sporadic attacks and kidnapping raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of opm's top executives come from Paniai, including Thadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested in Paniai in recent years and unjustifiably detained by the military under the pretext of "defending national independence."
Some never returned.
Among the population of Papua, Paniai is considered a "sad, forgotten place".
Poverty increases discontent.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
Bread is just as certainly unavailable.
People here grow everything they eat: mainly a note, but also some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can care for four to five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually save most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold at the local market.
Ten tubers of a note cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupiah (75 cents).
Over time, economic disparities have increased between native Papuans and new migrants, who have arrived in large numbers following the introduction of new flights to Nabiré Airport.
The few existing vacancies usually go to more educated and wealthy migrants.
Papuans rarely have enough money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive business.
"Young people don't want to stay in the village ... because there is no work or money here," says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Isolation keeps Papua away from the views of the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on the work of international media remain severe.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudy and Basile Longchamp were deported from Papua for "lack of coordination with relevant organisations" despite being given rare video permits.
According to Felim Keene, deputy director for Asia at Human Rights Watch, promises made during Jokowi's election campaign to lift restrictions on media work in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
"Now foreign journalists trying to report from the rebellious eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua, face new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of press attention means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely limited to Papua's immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific states – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands – asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "diverse and widespread violations" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
Those same countries have supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arramanatha Nasir brushed off the group's statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that "Indonesia still has a democratic system and a free press, so it would be difficult to hide evidence of human rights abuses."
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by dutch human rights ambassador Kiys Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, local residents broke their silence, saying, "We want freedom," according to a source who was also present at the meeting but wished to remain anonymous.
Indonesia will hold new presidential elections in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
"Jokowi is a man who has good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting," said Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the people of Paniai, in addition to living in the shadow of the threat from the greedy army, are mired in poverty, and their education and health care are in a miserable state.
Gobai says the people of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote for Jokowi to be a debt he must pay.
"They don't need money, they just want justice," he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting carried out the last symbolic act of defiance: they buried the body of one of the victims on a plot of land directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice will probably never be served, they at least won't let the guilty forget their crimes.
"They killed a member of our family," Jacobus says without raising his head.
"What else were we supposed to do?"
