EPA President Pruitt refuses to postpone the implementation of the rules adopted under Obama to reduce emissions
The day after the 15-state lawsuit, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency reversed his decision to postpone the implementation of Obama-era rules designed to reduce emissions of substances that pollute the air and lead to the formation of smog.
Pruitt explained his decision by the fact that now his agency listens more than under previous administrations to the needs of environmental regulators of individual states.
He made no mention of the lawsuit against his previous position filed in federal appeals court.
The dispute revolved around the Oct. 1 deadline by which states must meet 2015 standards for ground-level ozone.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would delay compliance for one year to give his agency more time to study the plan and avoid "inconsistencies with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth."
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma's attorney general before he was appointed by President Trump to his current position, has long been known as a consistent opponent of stricter environmental regulations.
Since moving to Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly blocked or delayed the imposition of regulations opposed by the chemical or gas-oil industries.
Wednesday's unexpected change of course is another legal defeat of Puitt's course of returning to previous norms.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the EPA had exceeded his authority in trying to delay the Obama administration's rule requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement Wednesday night, Pruitt suggested that by abruptly changing course on ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA's responsibility to work with states in a comprehensive process to implement the new standards in a timely manner.
"Under previous administrations, the EPA has often been unable to meet deadlines, after that it waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others and discussed timelines during the settlement of the case," said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
"We don't believe in regulation through litigation, and we take deadlines seriously.
We also take our charter and the power it gives us seriously."
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt could at some point again use his "deferral authority and other statutory powers" to make sure the norms are "on a clear course and on all available information."
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader overhaul of ozone rules.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, aims to delay implementation of the 2015 rules for at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on the issue.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led a coalition of states that filed a lawsuit against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
"The EPA's change of course — following our lawsuits — is an important victory in the fight for the health and safety of the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans who are directly affected by the smog that covers their cities," Schneiderman said.
California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, as well as the District of Columbia, joined the New York lawsuit.
Ground-level ozone occurs when common pollutants from machinery, power plants, refineries and chemical plants, and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems in sensitive people, leading to thousands of premature deaths per year.
Health and environmentalists welcomed Pruitt's unexpected change of course.
"It's sad to think about how much pressure it took to get this perfectly logical step from the person tasked with protecting the air we breathe," said Lori Ann Bird of the Center for Biodiversity.
"We must continue to resist the Trump administration's ideological campaign and protect those who pollute the air and their special interests."
