Morse Ford Murder: Activists Will Lose Lynch Trials on Stage to Call for Justice
A 1948 Ford Mercury drove past spectators in the village of Monroe, Georgia, and roared toward the small Morse Ford Bridge.
As a car carrying four black passengers and a white driver pulled up to the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked its path.
The main one, a middle-aged man in a thin-striped suit, tightened his cigar and looked through the windshield.
Those sitting inside trembled with fear.
"We need that nigger, Roger!" the man roared.
"Get him out of the car!"
Shrill screams broke the silence as a young black man was pulled out of the front seat.
Fortunately, this horrific scene, which played out on July 22, is just a dramatization.
But when a noose was thrown around Roger's neck, almost all the spectators really held their breath.
Since 2005, activists have been returning to Morse Ford Bridge to replay the night when two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and May Murray Dorsey, were lynched by Kukla klan in 1946.
No one has been convicted of these murders.
"It is striking that in all these years not a single person has been arrested - although we see them next to us; although we know who they are," says Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the production.
"It's a stain on our history and it's a rock on our souls."
Brooks, 71, is a former member of The Georgia Congress who has been fighting for human rights all his life.
For him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to monroe residents that the injustice has never been corrected.
"We want an investigation, we want completion, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice," he says.
"We cannot move to healing and reconciliation until we achieve justice."
The coroner covers the body of one of the victims of the Morse Ford lynching on July 27, 1946 with a sheet.
According to FBI records obtained by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of participating in the lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
Although the suspects have remained at large for decades, human rights activists say that the city has always been well aware of two related motives of vigilantes: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling for the first time allowed black citizens to vote in the primaries, which were to be held that summer.
Around the same election, the FBI reportedly stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, apparently because of a woman, in a fight.
Brooks says that according to rumors circulating in the city, Hester slept with Malcolm's wife Dorothy, and that the child she was supposed to give birth to was not from her husband.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a large white landowner, paid $600 in bail to free Malcolm from prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they drove out of jail and drove up to the Morse Ford Bridge, a mob of vigilantes surrounded the car.
"It turns out that Harrison organized and commanded the murders," one FBI report concludes.
"It is also clear that there was collusion between state and city law enforcement agencies, which not only took part in the killings, but also destroyed evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses."
Brooks calls it shorter.
"It was an attack on voting rights," he says.
"They were all killed to send a message to blacks in town: If you register and vote, it will be the same with you."
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Green has directed an annual play reproducing that lynching at Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is visual, it captures the viewer and tells about the deep racism, which, as many would like to believe, no longer exists in America.
It's hard to watch and even harder to turn away, but Green thinks that's the main thing.
"We don't want to talk about the Lynch Courts because they show us our own ugliness," she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you unless you hear me or hear what I've been through."
Rehearsals for this year's play began in June, and on the first day nearly 30 actors — a dozen whites, the rest black — gathered indoors and listened to a review of the play polished over the years.
Wade Marbo directed along with Green.
He played the role of the main member of the clan for several years, but says that the role never got easier.
"I feel like I got dirty because it's not the kind of person I am," Marbo says.
"But I think it's very important to remember that story because we don't want to go back to that time."
Indoors, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, reprise their roles.
The spectacle begins with Malcolm, furious that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said,, get out of my house!"
Rascon shouts back.
A blow is heard.
And at the same moment, everyone (at least all the black actors) burst into laughter.
Green laughs the loudest.
"What's that," Askona asks.
He is concerned and confused.
Am I overplaying?
"No," Green says through laughter.
"I just don't think whites said '' then."
"Yes, yes," laughs one of the black performers.
"You have to pronounce a solid 'r'."
And so does the energy in the room change: discomfort is replaced by a sense of camaraderie.
Everyone has to do everything right, not only for the sake of the play, but also for the memory of the four people killed.
The scene starts over.
This time, when Rascona says a word for the letter "n", it turns out to be clear and sharp.
Not a single person laughs.
The play ends violently and quickly.
Screams, gunshots, and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands over the bodies of the actors and performs Billie Holiday's sad song "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is interrupted by a word.
A hundred yards away, fifty spectators wipe tears and sweat from their eyes.
There are almost equal numbers of blacks and whites among the audience.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York to watch the performance; many live very close.
They all endured Georgia's heavy stuffiness for nearly eight hours as Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the graves of malcolm and Dorsey.
Up to this point, the murders remained only history, but now, when they stand in the same place where people were lynched, it seems that their ghosts are in the air.
When the last note of the song subsides, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
Children bend over to their heads, touch blood paint and motionless bodies, and whisper something to each other.
"They're not really dead," mutters one little boy, as if to remind himself.
A few minutes later, Green thanks the audience, and suddenly it's over.
The actors shed ropes from their necks and wipe away tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, a man in a suit who played the main Ku Klux Klan.
Nick Rascona hugs the other two actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional load of the performance finally fell on him.
"It's okay," one woman whispers.
"We know you have a good heart.
You had reasons for that."
Later, the audience sits down to dinner with the actors.
At the same table, a white couple from Atlanta animatedly discusses a play with a black couple they have just met.
Denise Daplinsky struggles to find the words to describe how she feels after the performance.
"It's hard to listen to these horrible, creepy words, and actions... people who look like you and who do it because they look like you," she says.
"After that, I think the lynchings are still happening," she adds, "only now it's called what the police are shooting."
In another corner of the room, Tyrone Brooks, who recalls his work as a human rights activist over food.
He says he has already started planning next year's performance.
"The production inspires us because it not only describes the horror of what we have experienced, but also teaches us," he says.
"Because if you don't learn from that, it could happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it."
