New test results published to assess the age of asylum seekers in Sweden
The latest test results of asylum seekers in Sweden who were subjected to a new method of medical age assessment show that more than 80 percent of those tested were assessed as over 18 years of age, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Forensic Medicine Agency (Rättsmedicinalverket) began conducting tests earlier this year.
They were designed to make age estimates in the asylum process more accurate, after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the true age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
So far, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the forensic agency has now released the results of 2,481 tests between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of those tested were rated as 18 years of age or older, and in another 25 cases, the forensic science agency rated that the test taker was "probably a person 18 years of age or older."
In the case of 432 cases, the opinion stated that the person was "probably under 18".
Tests are carried out only in cases where the person's age is in doubt.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are in line with those of past months.
"We don't see much difference with the statistics for the past months, the numbers are quite appropriate," he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which people were assessed as having reached the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum-seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases, "most likely, the age of the test taker is 18 years or more."
However, after reviewing 581 published results, the newspaper "Svenska Dagbladet" found that in 243 cases a person openly stated that he turned 18 this year.
The method of conducting a medical age assessment, consisting of making x-rays of wisdom teeth and tomography of the knee joints and giving them for analysis to dentists and radiologists, also caused criticism in some instances.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institutet, whose work is to assess the biological maturity of people in order to determine whether they have gone through puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I had reasons to think about it, and I don't think you need to use the methods of measurement that are used now.
Biological age is thus determined very inaccurately.
If we can't define it with certainty, we shouldn't pretend we can," he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Göranssen of the Forensic Medicine Agency spoke in favor of the accuracy of the tests: "In general, it can be said that the risk of mistaken a child for an adult is small.
The biggest risk we face is when a person is about 18, in which case he is about 10 percent. "
