How football's financial rules will affect Neymar's move to Paris
Rules aimed at preventing unlimited spending by European football clubs will not prevent the world-record-setting transfer of Neymar from the Spanish Barcelona to the French Paris Saint-Germain.
Any consequences could come further down the chain for Paris Saint-Germain from UEFA, the governing body that oversees European football, whose power to ban teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League tournament.
From the rules of financial "fair play", introduced by UEFA in 2011, it follows that PSG will eventually have to show that the transfer of Neymar was financed without major losses.
Barcelona were paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to release the Brazilian from his contract, and Neymar will receive a salary that will reach tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some financial aspects of Neymar's move to France.
PSG could definitely fork out to hire Neymar and add him to the galaxy of other stars, given the team's funding from Qatar's energy-rich ruling family.
Clubs have the right to spend large sums to acquire players, but they have to balance them with legitimate sources of income in order to reach the threshold of profitability in their football business.
FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former French footballer believed that clubs that went into huge debt in their quest for success were essentially cheating and risking ruin if banks or owners stopped financing.
In 2011, FFP stopped focusing on the clubs' debts and instead switched to tracking their losses.
As a consequence of this change, the business model that Roman Abramovich originally used at Chelsea in 2003 – to buy a club with good potential and then spend heavily to improve the team and create a global brand – has become a difficult plan.
During the current three-year evaluation period, which is exciting in 2018, clubs could suffer losses of €30 million.
And, despite the fact that Platini was disgracefully removed from the presidency in 2015, his successor in UEFA, Alexander Ceferin, is still determined to restrain excessive spending.
"Of course, the FFP is alive and we will tighten the rules as we move forward," Andrea Traverso, who controls the FFP at UEFA, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG will pay for the purchase of Neymar's contract in a lump sum, he can distribute this amount for reporting throughout the term of his contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer value can be shown in the annual accounts as an expense of 44.4 million euros over the next five years.
During the first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014, PSG, as well as Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City, were subjected to severe sanctions.
PSG were fined €60 million (at that rate of $82 million), which was later reduced to €20 million, and were ordered to limit their team's champions league roster during the 2014-1015 season to 21 players instead of the usual 25.
UEFA tracks clubs that may try to outsmart its financial supervisors by inflating their revenue at the expense of companies linked to the club's owners.
Although the Qatari company could sponsor PSG, but if the amount of financing was considered to exceed the standard market rates, UEFA would not allow it to be considered legitimate income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA ruled that the amount of funding for PSG from the Qatar Tourism Authority had been inflated.
It was reported that part of Neymar's earnings at PSG could come in the form of payments from the organizing committee of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 deny that Neymar will become an ambassador for the World Cup, and such a maneuver could easily be detected by UEFA inspectors.
Past sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will monitor even more closely any attempts to circumvent the rules.
As reported on Thursday by persons familiar with the situation, UEFA did not conduct preliminary discussions with PSG about the transfer of Neymar.
They spoke to the Associated Press on condition of anonymity as they are not authorized to discuss PSG's position.
According to the latest published reports, in 2015-1016, PSG received more than 10 million euros of profit with a turnover of 542.4 million euros.
The financial statements for the last financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expects that the arrival of Neymar will be a fertile ground for sponsorship deals, the sale of paraphernalia and shirts with the team's logo.
The club expects turnover to grow by at least 30 percent as a result of hiring a new player.
Undoubtedly angry that one of the best players was leaving, the Spanish league tried to prevent the transfer of Neymar, saying that PSG would violate the financial "fair play".
"This is an obvious case of 'financial doping', with the club and the state," La Liga president Javier Tebas told the Spanish newspaper AS, referring to Qatar as the ultimate owner.
Arsenal coach Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports tycoon, shares La Liga's doubts about the club's funding by the state.
"These are all the consequences of equity participation, and it has completely changed the landscape of football over the past fifteen years," Wenger said on Thursday.
"When a club belongs to a country, anything is possible.
It becomes very difficult to comply with financial fair play because a country can have many paths and many reasons to be represented by such a serious player.
The order and places of taking the oath will be determined by the President
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the president - such amendments to the second reading to the relevant law were developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Construction.
A week ago, deputies planned to directly determine the procedure for taking the oath in the law.
Children under 18 years of age, as well as those who are incapacitated, will be exempt from taking a solemn oath, follows from the revised text of the amendments to the bill "On Citizenship of the Russian Federation" (available to Izvestia), which the committee will consider before the second reading at its meeting on July 11.
The idea of introducing an oath when entering into Russian citizenship instead of formally signing documents was supported by President Vladimir Putin on June 6 during a meeting with State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies formalized this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading to the bill providing for the abolition of the decision to issue citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public calls to terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (Part 2 of Article 205.2 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as for hijacking an airplane,  trains or water transport, but only if this act is related to terrorism (Part 4 of Article 211 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
According to the bill, its logic was as follows: when applying for citizenship, a person signs a promise to comply with Russian legislation - by embarking on the path of extremism, he violates this promise.
The bill was submitted to the State Duma in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasilyev ("United Russia"), Gennady Zyuganov (CPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov ("Fair Russia") and the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the State Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been revised once again.
Now it says that the order of taking the oath will be established by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On Citizenship of the Russian Federation", indicating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn atmosphere in front of the state emblem and flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - the list of places where it is possible to place the coat of arms of the Russian Federation is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include the courts, the offices of the heads of state authorities of the regions, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could be registry offices.
Those wishing to obtain Russian citizenship will pronounce a solemn oath after officials check their documents.
But a person will receive a Russian passport only after he takes the oath, follows from the revised text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that Russia will be sworn in from the age of 18, and not from 14.
The rule has been preserved according to which the incapacitated or limited legal capacity, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or personally sign the text of the oath, will be exempted from taking the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt from this procedure and "other persons",
Also, the updated bill prescribes a special procedure for the admission of Russian citizens to residents of Ukraine who are considered native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to officially renounce Ukrainian citizenship by submitting a corresponding application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
The renunciation of "foreign" nationality, as it is now, will not be required if it is provided for in an international treaty or if this is not possible "for reasons beyond the control of the person".
The corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, including First Deputy Speaker of the State Duma Ivan Melnikov (CpRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Airat Farrakhov (all from United Russia).
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is unrealistic, simply impossible.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for the decision of their fate regarding the citizenship of the Russian Federation, - explained on the eve of the head of the Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation Pavel Krasheninnikov (UR).
In addition, the text clarified that restrictions on holding certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who have writtenly renounced "other" citizenship and handed over the previous passport to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but "for reasons beyond his control" he has not ceased to be considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are forbidden to hold positions in the municipal service, to be hired at facilities and organizations whose activities are related to ensuring the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or a residence permit of another country cannot become a deputy of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should come into force on September 1, 2017, by which time the necessary by-laws should be ready.
Nostalgia becomes a niche in "Hot American Summer" and "Comrade Detective"
The current iteration of the story is nostalgically reminiscent of the characters' glorious days in the '80s; about the era of grunge in the 90s (around the time when the outstanding masters David Wayne and Michael Schowalter made the comedy sketches "The State" for MTV); and about herself - that is, about 2001, before her stars, as Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler and Paul Rudd moved on to more serious things.
As a fact of culture, it is both the rise and embodiment of our era with its constant reminders from Facebook.
But as a franchise, it seems anachronistic.
"The First Day of Camp" was surprisingly good, and not just because of the absurdist humor (including the original story of a talking can of vegetables, which was voiced by H. John Benjamin).
The result doubles the main joke: middle-aged actors play sexually anxious children who have just reached adulthood; thanks to this, the inability to return to the joke becomes part of the joke.
Ten Years Later, where adults played adults, has less deep emotional roots, and its parody is more haphazard and includes riffs from '90s stalker films like The Hand Rocking the Cradle.
In one episode, the character pulls out an Apple Powerbook, four-wheeled roller skates, and "a bunch of other things from 1991."
Many of the plot moves are the same.
Good-natured Koop (Showalter), now a writer, still hasn't gotten any reciprocity from Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) still hasn't given up his virginity.
And then there's the crazy and dastardly conspiracy involving Ronald Reagan (also Showalter), who is now instigated by George H.W. Bush (a tried and tested parody played by Michael Ian Blake).
As always, the best part of the franchise is deviating from it.
It's especially funny to see the eternally young Rudd humming Matt Dillon's song from Loners, whose character, the former big man Andy, now looks like an old man.
The franchise could be successful with occasional follies like the recursive series Seven Up, until it gets to what I think would be its logical conclusion: "A Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later," where in the last scene the whole company would go to the cinema for the premiere of the film "Hot American Summer."
"Comrade Detective" on Amazon appeals to another type of nostalgia: memories of the Cold War from "The Americans," "Explosive Blonde," or even "Glitter," with its images of East-West struggles.
This comedy, created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaca with director Reese Thomas, depicts a TV movie: a Romanian police drama of the 80s about two policemen in Bucharest fighting for truth, atheism and the Marxist-Leninist way.
The main roles - gregor who has seen the life and the idealist Josef - are performed by Florin Piersik Jr. and Corneliu Ulić, and their dialogues in English are voiced by Channing Tatum (he is also an executive producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levitte.
It's a brilliant idea.
But just an idea.
There are a few visual jokes (police officers spend time watching a chess match, just as Americans might watch football).
A team of famous voice-over voices - among them Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloe Sevigny - allows you to play "guess the voice" in an interesting way.
But "Comrade Detective" clings so much to the plausibility of a clumsy propaganda drama — there's even a killer in a Ronald Reagan mask — that it often looks like it.
Six long episodes are drawn out, and it's not very funny, not often.
Had it been made shorter, Comrade Detective might have done a better job of its agitprop-esque satire; for example, every time Gregor and Josef arrive at the American embassy, two fat men sit in the lobby devouring a bunch of hamburgers.
To the imaginary communist viewer, this image tells us that Western culture can make a gluttony out of anything.
The fictional Romanian filmmakers are not so wrong: We do this even with our own recent history, and with theirs too.
