The bank's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6-to-2 to keep rates at 0.25%, with fewer members of the committee calling for a rate hike this month because weak economic growth weakened support for the hike.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank limited its upward forecasts to 1.7% in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018 and warned that pressure on household incomes would continue, while inflation is still expected to rise to around 3% in the fall.
However, the bank warned that rate hikes in the next few years would be needed to control Brexit-induced inflation and said borrowing costs would likely have to be raised more than expected in financial markets.
Also, members of the committee voted to abandon part of the huge set of measures for the development of the economy, launched a year ago as a result of Brexit.
Starting next February, the bank will close a term financing plan under which it provides banks with cheap loans, although it said it now has to provide another 15 billion pounds under this plan - up to 115 billion pounds.
In its rate decision minutes, the bank said: "According to the MPC's core forecasts, gross domestic product (GDP) growth in the near term remains slow, while pressures on real household incomes continue to weigh on consumption."
On the issue of rates, he reiterated that in order to stop inflation, "some tightening of financial policy" would be required, at a "slightly larger" rate than the markets expected.
At the moment, markets are predicting the first increase in the third quarter of next year and another in 2020.
But the bank stressed that all increases will be "gradual" and "limited."
The bank's forecasts for an increase this year and next year are lower than forecasts made in May, which were equal to 1.9% and 1.7%.
The bank left unchanged its forecast of 1.8% in 2018.
