NHS to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Starting in September, patients will have access to a "revolutionary" HIV prevention drug after a High Court battle over funding for the drug from the NHS.
The National Health Service of England has announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis for HIV (PrEP), a pre-sex pill that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in people at risk by an average of 86 per cent, will now be provided by health services over an initial three-year probationary period of approximately 10,000 people.
She agreed to fund the trial after an appeals court upheld a High Court ruling last year arguing that the NHS had the ability to pay for the PrEP despite its claims it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, which was announced on Thursday, was described as a "major innovation" by National Health Service England President Simon Stevens, and the National AIDS Control Authority (NAT) called it a "turning point".
Ahead of the full launch of the programme across England by April 2018, venereal dispensaries in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start registering people, with even more dispensaries joining the programme in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV medications taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
When taking PrEP before sex in the human body, there are enough certain drugs to prevent infection with HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Eligible patients include gay and bisexual men, transgender people and people whose partners are HIV-positive and do not receive successful treatment.
Dispensaries will select eligible participants who agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people and individuals whose partners are not known whether their HIV status is contained by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and assigned to a GP in England will also be able to apply for potential participation in the nearest venereal disease dispensary taking part in the programme.
The programme will cost £10 million, and England's National Health Service this week signed a contract to provide the drug after an international procurement tender.
The study is structured in such a way as to assess the full possibilities of PrEP by collecting clinical data on who is the target audience of the drug, its digestibility and use on a large scale.
"This critical innovation should complement and strengthen large-scale and increasingly successful hiv prevention efforts.
This is another milestone in more than three decades of success in the fight against one of the biggest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, President of NAT (National AIDS Control Authority), said: "This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if properly targeted at people in need of help and at risk, provides an opportunity to change the state of affairs with the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at risk for HIV will have access to a new, empowering tool that a person can control without discussing it with a partner through this study in England, which will improve many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this news."
Ian Green, president of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: "The first priority now is to ensure that the trial unfolds quickly across the country and that no one at risk for HIV is left behind.
Now that we are provided with the experimental drug PrEP, we are on our way to protecting the more than 10,000 people at risk for HIV."
