In Russia, there were difficulties in obtaining an international driver's license
Traffic police units are experiencing a shortage of international driver's licenses (IDPs).
To get such a license, you have to wait in line for several weeks, which has become a real problem for vacationers who want to go on vacation abroad in their car or rent it there.
It is worth noting that the situation with international driving permits remains contradictory.
The IDP was introduced to make it easier for the foreign police to understand what is written in the national identity card, since the information in it is explained in five languages.
Requirements for international rights are written in the Vienna Convention on Road Traffic of 1968, but in countries that have ratified the Vienna Convention, Russian rights are recognized as such.
However, in reality, it all depends on the specific police or rental office: some require an IDP, and someone has enough national rights.
To hedge their bets, drivers still receive international rights, but it should be borne in mind that in countries that have not ratified the convention (for example, the USA, Spain, Mexico, Indonesia), the authorities have the right not to recognize either national rights or IDPs.
Now there is a problem with forms in almost all traffic police units, Kommersant reports, having conducted a study in a number of regions.
So, in Moscow, in the units of the traffic police, coupons are simply not issued, the forms have not been enough for four months.
You can make an appointment on the website of public services, but there the queue has already stretched until mid-August.
In Krasnoyarsk, it is impossible to get an IDP "for technical reasons" without going into details, in the Samara region they honestly say that there are no forms, a similar situation is developing in other cities.
