Judges are proposed to be protected from presidents
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of court presidents and introduce their electability.
For the courts of appeal and cassation instances, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential instruction.
The HRC has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of the Russian judiciary.
The HRC carried out this work on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with members of the Council.
At a meeting with members of the council on December 8, 2016, individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens were discussed (see "Kommersant" of December 9).
As a result of the work of the HRC, 25 proposals were made, which relate both to the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and identifying miscarriages of justice, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin's human rights activists is to limit the powers of court chairmen in order to increase the independence of other judges.
If a candidate for the post of judge has successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, then the chairman of the court, in the opinion of the HRC, should submit him for appointment, not having the right to refuse, as the law allows now.
It is also proposed to deprive the president of the right to distribute cases for consideration among judges.
To do this, experts admit, can a specially written computer program.
Also, the HRC believes that the chairman does not have the right to "predetermine the results of the qualification certification of a judge, initiate his bringing to disciplinary responsibility, make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments."
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to "the election of court chairmen by the judges themselves" and "to give them powers for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation."
Now all the chairmen of the courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the president on the proposal of the chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the HRC proposes to organize appeal and cassation in courts of general jurisdiction in a new way.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts."
Experts take as a basis the practice of arbitration courts.
Under them, there are "judicial districts" that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but thereby guarantee greater independence from regional officials who find it difficult to use the "telephone law".
The HRC proposes to strengthen the justices of the peace with people's assessors in order to consider certain "categories of civil and administrative cases" with their participation.
For example, on the deprivation of parental rights, on reinstatement at work, on the protection of honor and dignity, on the deprivation of a driver's license, etc.
"These are only our proposals," Tamara Morshchakova, a member of the HRC, a retired judge of the Constitutional Court, explained to Kommersant.
She also recalled that the president's instruction applied not only to the HRC, but also to the Supreme Court (SC), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
The Supreme Court still has time to fulfill the order (among the co-executors are the Prosecutor General's Office and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation).
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation, the Chairman of the Supreme Court Vyacheslav Lebedev must before September 1.
Living a high life: a half-storey floor and cunning design techniques have turned this small apartment in Earls Court into a spacious dwelling
Joan Lee, a former banker with a passion for real estate renovations, moved from a spacious home in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is located on the first floor of a cute standard house in the style of Queen Anne, and in favor of the new design says that Joan did not pack her things and did not move again.
"I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge in a much larger area," says Joan.
"I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and there were the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered the price the same day."
Since the first viewing, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
Originally, it was a one-bedroom apartment of a complex layout – to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-floor to get the most out of the generous ceiling heights.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands," she says.
To that end, she hired Erfan Azadi of The Duck & Shed, an architectural and design studio in Notting Hill, to use the 12.5-foot-tall ceilings and create a dwelling that would not only be a successful project, but would be suitable for Joan's living.
The ceiling was not high enough to arrange two rooms one above the other, so the architectural task was to create a half-floor where it would be possible to stand in full growth.
Erfan had to think creatively to cope with the brief.
"Working with steel structures is very difficult," he explains.
"We needed to arrange the rooms so that they were one above the other, and we did not have to bend.
It was necessary not just to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed the use of rooms from above and below. "
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-size rooms one above the other in the allotted space - and many more interesting things.
From the half-floor through the vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius" you can see the chic living room below.
Mirrored furniture with golden finishes, silver accents and vintage lighting fixtures from Serge Mooye set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, spaciousness and light.
The short corridor is framed by mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, the mirrored protective panel seems to be a window to another room.
At the entrance, mirrored cabinets serve to store all of Joan's utensils.
To create the feeling of a more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can block the kitchen when it is not used.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a sliding up door, like in a garage.
"Engineering was involved here," Erfan says of the steel-reinforced wood-fiber shield door.
"It's equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily."
Thanks to the judicious use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
"At the end of the day, floor space is exactly what you're going to sell, that is, what your property is valued against," says Erfan.
"Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the floor area."
Here, they were able to increase the floor area using quality materials that give the space a touch of luxury.
"Materials are something we touch, so they help create an emotional connection to the home," says Erfan.
"No one falls in love with the electrical wiring in the walls.
It's important, but it doesn't touch the strings of our hearts."
This serves as evidence that due to good design and increased footage, the apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you may decide to stay.
