The brothers fight for a real estate empire worth more than $ 500 million
The two brothers are fighting over one of Victoria's largest empires in the more than $500 million property trade — forty years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
Former Carleton Football Club director and real estate developer Colin de Lutis lives in the Turak Palace three doors from his younger brother Paul, who has filed a Supreme Court action against him for the division of possessions and assets.
Paul has been wanting to leave the family business since 2014, but there has been a bitter dispute in the Supreme Court over the terms of the divorce.
Along with their mother Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, bought since their family bought a store in Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded the company "Westco Jeans", which grew into a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the list of de Lutis family's possessions includes today office buildings, building plots in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and in Mount Buller, and shopping centers in the suburbs.
By arrangement with his late father, Colin — whom Paul describes as the "main driving force and dominant personality" of the De Lutis family — owns roughly two-thirds of the company's assets, and Paul owns about one-third.
According to the court, this means that Colin's property is 316 million and Paul's is 176 million.
The division of property and money became a stumbling block for Paul.
"The section proposed by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of the property," he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
Last Friday, after several failed attempts at reconciliation, the first hearings in the Supreme Court took place.
The brothers are now arguing over who will control the existing business — from which Paul believes Colin has excluded him.
Colin claims that this is not the case, but accuses Paul of incompetent management of some objects.
In testimony given by Colin at the beginning of the trial, he says he hopes for a resolution of the dispute.
"My Italian roots make me consider family a top priority," he wrote.
Legal costs are snowballing, with hundreds of pages of testimony, emails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer attached to the case; both sides brought in some of the most prominent lawyers, including M.C., Allan Myers, and the best.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband Luigi were immigrants from Italy; from the late 1950s they ran dairy bars and deli, and in the early 1970s bought a shop in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood, in which Colin opened the first family jeans store.
Colin says he started Westco when he was "in the last grades of school, and Paul was then a boy (about 10 years old)."
Anna De Lutis says she and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to pass on their possessions to their sons without conflict.
"Luigi often told me he didn't want the brothers to look into court," she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutis group of companies; Colina says Mark got 10 million when he went out of business, and Luke got 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were "dissatisfied with the financial conditions of their separation."
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the board of directors of the AFL club and, according to a biography published in 2015 of Eddie McGuire, the best friend of the TV star.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin responded with a text message saying that since the case hadn't yet been tried, "I really don't have much to say."
"I am very, very sorry that my brother Paul has decided to sue me and rattle the name of our family in court," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in testimony that he was trying to meet his brother's demands.
"Our father wouldn't want to see Paul and I arguing in court," he said, adding that he was "still hoping for a resolution of the conflict."
On Friday, that hope seems to have dissipated.
"The decision in our case will be made by the court soon," Colin wrote.
Trump's new chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information to the president.
Others tried to do so and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly will actually succeed.
In this case, it will be the first.
Politico says the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information to President Trump, including news reports from the media, hoping to keep the chief calmer.
Here's what reporter Josh Dawsey reports.
"At a meeting held by the new White House Chief of Staff John F. Kelly with the leadership of the staff on his first working day, he outlined the main problem in the White House under President Donald Trump, which he hopes to solve: poor channels of information to the president."
Kelly told employees that information should flow through him — in paper form or through briefings — because the president would be better at making decisions if he got the right information.
Kelly's diagnosis is completely correct, but others have already failed in trying to pacify Trump by tracking the flow of information to him.
President Trump's relationship with television developed decades ago — and now that he's in the White House, his TV habit is still strong.
"When Trump, as a candidate, resented unfair campaign coverage, it was helpful to demonstrate to him that he was getting fair coverage in publications that could be persuaded," Sam Nanberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri wrote in Politico at the time that "according to six former members of the campaign, in order to keep Trump's habit of tweeting under control, it was necessary to ensure that there was a constant stream of praise in the information coming to him personally."
Ok.
But the idea that Trump's Habit of Tweeting has ever been "under control" is ridiculous.
Maybe these campaign members know something we don't — like that if it weren't for them, Trump's tweets would be even more provocative.
We may never know about tweets that Trump didn't release.
If his staff saved him from trouble at least a few times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has always been able to deter Trump from adding fuel to the fire.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to push their agenda by feeding Trump material — reliable or not — that confirms their views.
"Politico" - just for this story - wrote in May about the tendency of advisers to constantly slip the president dubious information.
Here's one example, described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
Current and former Trump employees say Trump can react very harshly to negative press coverage, especially those containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds who was behind them.
That's what happened in late February, when someone slipped the president a printout of an article from GotNews.com, the website of Internet provocateur Charles K. Johnson, in which Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Welsh was accused of "standing behind a series of leaks" in the White House.
