Italy is toughening its tone towards NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs that own rescue vessels in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue operating unless they obey the new rules governing their activities.
"If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turin-based daily Stampa.
Minniti's warning came a day after Italian authorities confiscated a vessel belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which has only worked for a year, declined to comment on the merits of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartozio.
"For us, saving human life is and will remain the highest priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue activities in the search and rescue zone now," the organization said in a statement on social networks.
"We will only be able to assess all the allegations made now after we have gathered all the information and are able to assess the situation."
Italian authorities have been monitoring the Juventa vessel, owned by jugend rettet, since October.
Its crew is suspected of taking on board migrants who were sent directly to them by lifeboats and allowing smugglers to leave with boats they could reuse.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast, according to the prosecution materials, the content of which was published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the regulations of the Italian coastal authorities, who monitor rescue operations in this zone, more out of humanitarian zeal than for any other reason.
The code of conduct assumes, mainly, that the Juventa-class vessels will have on board an Italian police officer who will monitor their activities.
So far, only three of nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to comply with the code: Save the Children, Malta's MOAS and Pro-Activa Open Arms from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday it considered the new rules unnecessary but acceptable as long as they did not entail any "meaningful changes or interference" with its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign is the Nobel Prize-winning Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said the sharp decline in recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicates that efforts to support the Libyan coast guard and cooperation with local mayors are bearing fruit.
"In recent days, we have started to see light at the end of the tunnel," the minister said.
He outlined plans for further talks with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
"In Libya, we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict"
The Russian authorities have recently noticeably intensified their policy in the Libyan direction, and delegations of the opposing Libyan parties often visited Moscow.
The head of the Russian contact group on the intra-Libyan settlement under the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, an assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic, Lev Dengov, told Kommersant what goals Moscow pursues in this region and on whom it relies.
Almost nothing is known about the contact group on Libya, which you are chairing.
For example, the contact group on Ukraine – everyone knows about it.
And here is the veil of secrecy.
What exactly do you do, what goals do you pursue?
The contact group was established at the initiative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Duma deputy from Chechnya. - "Kommersant").
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker "Mechanic Chebotarev" (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - "Kommersant").
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group of military specialists, representatives of the State Duma was created, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
And how did it happen that you headed it?
Since I have been working on Libya since 2008, I was approached to lead the group.
Our activities were not limited to the release of sailors from the Chebotarev Mechanic.
We managed to establish contacts with representatives of all the main groups opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government led by Fayez Sarraj is based. - "Kommersant"), and with Tobruk (the residence of the parliament, which opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya. - "Kommersant").
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Deputy Prime Minister of Libya - "Kommersant"), we managed to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided, in order to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, and engage in dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I want to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict, we are engaged in a dialogue with everyone.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
Now the contact group includes five people.
Among them there are people with experience in law enforcement agencies, including the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to introduce representatives of the Institute of the Middle East of the Russian Academy of Sciences into the group of specialists in the region.
None of our employees are permanently in Libya, there is no need for this yet.
Are there any Russian military advisers and instructors in Libya now?
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this do not correspond to reality.
But your contact group includes former military personnel...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or such closed cities as Misrata (where militia units that played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and noticeably intensified in subsequent years) are based. - "Kommersant").
We arrived in Misrata in January this year.
We were frightened, they said that everyone there was all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there ourselves, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the real role of the Islamists there.
In Misrata, we met with all representatives of the detachments that were engaged in the destruction of isIS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the Islamic State banned in Russia - "Kommersant").
We wanted to look at them, get to know these people, check the information that they played a decisive role in the destruction of ISIS in Libya, and not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed to himself these merits.
And what conclusion did you come to?
Is it not Haftar who defeated the Islamic State in Libya?
He didn't do it.
Haftar conducted operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And isIS in Sirte was fought by structures subordinate to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited to Russia the people who conducted this anti-terrorist operation.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from April 19 to April 23 of this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, in the Duma, the Foreign Ministry and Rosgvardia.
As we understand, you visit all Libyan regions and probably imagine the mood of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the agreements on a ceasefire, on the holding of elections that Khalifa Haftar and Fayez Sarraj reached in Paris at the end of July?
Or again, as has happened many times in the past, will the agreements be disrupted, hostilities will resume, the parties will try to seize power alone?
For us, a good signal was the fact that Sarraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, both leaders spoke extremely negatively about each other.
As for Russia's position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe in this.
We encountered this situation when we were in Misrata, and Haftar was on this very day boarding the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But Misrata did not believe in a coincidence.
We were told: "You are probably very brave people who came to us today."
But our task is precisely to show that we do not support only Haftar, we are engaged in dialogue with all key parties to the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar communicated.
Does the mutual understanding with Russian partners at the human, emotional level facilitate the fact that he studied twice in the USSR?
And, by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
If he knows Russian, it is very relative.
But the fact that he studied with us, of course, facilitates a dialogue with him.
And by the way, not only with him.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And now they speak perfect Russian.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent they feel nostalgia for it.
Do you think that the arms embargo imposed on Libya will soon be lifted?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but, as I have already said, we do not take sides in this conflict and would not like to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, libyans constantly call for Russia to somehow contribute to its lifting.
Now in Libya, the process of drafting a constitution is actively progressing.
We hope that the parties will reach compromise solutions and achieve an internal consensus.
Then elections should be held, which was discussed at the meeting between Sarraj and Haftar.
If elections are held and a legitimate government is finally elected (and now none of the parties has such a status), then we can raise the issue of lifting the arms embargo in the UN Security Council.
Raising this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
The other day, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, feels abandoned to the mercy of fate by its EU allies.
Can Moscow help its Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is it that Haftar's forces would take control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers transporting immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need Russia's support because Moscow is engaged in a dialogue simultaneously with Haftar, Sarraj, Misrata and the south of the country.
And in this matter, tribes in the south of Libya play a big role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about southerners stopping the flow of migrants on the distant approaches?
That is, relatively speaking, they turned back the buses in which Nigerian migrants are traveling?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these streams going.
We hope to help unite the southerners in the negotiation process between Sarraj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But first, we would like to see a unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Sarraj.
The head of government in Tripoli, Fayez Sarraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of Sharia norms in the country.
How radical is he?
Will this not become an obstacle in building relations with Russia or the West?
I will express my personal opinion about him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But there are Islamists in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself adheres to the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And he is also actively fighting terrorists.
Where does he get that reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is, after all, the capital, there is a legislative, executive and judicial power.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in us not going there.
And we mixed all the cards for them and began to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has signed a cooperation agreement with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
NOC Director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rosneft CEO Igor Sechin made the deal, is himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess resell.
And what are Russia's economic interests in Libya?
There are plans to re-sign contracts concluded under Muammar Gaddafi.
We are talking, in particular, about previous agreements in the transport sector (construction of railways), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do Libyans have something to pay?
Well, they have oil.
That is, as in the case of Iran, we are talking about the "oil for services" scheme?
I do not know what the scheme will be, I do not deal directly with these issues.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We are, in fact, engaged in peacekeeping work there.
For us, the main thing is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans to come to an agreement among themselves, so that they can establish order in their country and Libya ceases to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task - to help the Libyan people and squeeze out the terrorists from there.
Do you have any data on the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that to date, not a single immigrant from Russia and other countries of the former USSR is there.
He said that he has about 50 thousand records of telephone conversations of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - "Kommersant") and Russian speech does not sound there.
And from which states then are these militants?
I wouldn't want to go into those details.
Then let's phrase the question differently.
How many Of the Islamist militants in Libya are Libyans themselves?
There are practically no Libyans among them, they are no more than 5%.
The rest are newcomers.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks following the example of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are conducting active negotiations with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have declared their readiness to come again - to Moscow or to Grozny.
And when can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say now.
There are still a few visits to be made, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of the talks.
