Michelle Carter's sentence for reports prompting the suicide of Conrad Roy
A resident of Massachusetts was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for the fact that she used text messages and phone calls to induce the suicide of her boyfriend Conrad Roy.
Michelle Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months of her sentence behind bars and another 5 years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father told Thursday's hearing: "My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to remain at large pending appeal.
She faced a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red pants and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing, clenching her hands and lowering her eyes.
"By her actions, she killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She did not acknowledge responsibility," she said.
"She showed no remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said it was a "tragic incident that she deeply regrets."
However, Judge Lawrence Moniz said he believed her "age, maturity level or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions".
The prosecutor read out statements from Roy's mother, Lynn Roy, which said: "Not a single day has passed when I would not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I cope – I try to support his sisters despite all the pain that will stay with us forever," it reads.
Roy's sister Camdeen Roy said she was relentlessly haunted by the thought that she could never attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"To lose a person who has always been with me since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life," she said.
The case appears to set a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that provides for responsibility for advising a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The incident attracted the attention of the whole country when it became known that he was pushed to suicide by Carter's messages.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife I don't know there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was vacationing with his family.
Minutes before her suicide, she wrote, "You have to do it, Conrad," and "You just have to turn on the ignition and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Moniz said Carter wanted attention through Roy's death and forbade her from talking to the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of lawyers on this issue are divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 for the murder in Italy of her British flatmate and acquitted two years later.
Knox, 30, posted a dissenting opinion in the Los Angeles Times, stating, "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
