Audi will have to modify up to 850,000 diesel cars
A day before the announcement from Audi, BMW said it would offer software updates to more than 350,000 vehicles.
BMW's chairman said the company believes "there are more intelligent ways than driving restrictions," referring to European cities — including Munich, where BMW is based — that have considered banning or restricting the use of diesel cars.
Daimler said on Thursday it would modify three million Mercedes vehicles in Europe to reduce their diesel exhaust.
None of the companies called their move a recall.
European automakers have actively promoted the use of diesel cars in Europe and the United States to promote compliance with carbon dioxide emission regulations.
But the nitrogen oxides that diesel engines emit are considered carcinogens and can cause asthma.
The cost to automakers of installing equipment that neutralizes the exhaust gases of diesel cars is also rising, and maintaining a competitive price for cars is becoming difficult.
