Astronomers have found a "hellish" planet on which even iron can melt
Having first studied the properties of the stratosphere of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, astrophysicists were quite surprised by its temperature, which is able to evaporate iron and other metals.
Experts have noticed that water molecules are so heated by the light of the star that they emit infrared radiation.
The Hubble telescope captured the radiance of water molecules on this gas giant: this high temperature causes the water in the planet's atmosphere to glow in the infrared range.
WASP-121b belongs to the so-called "hot Jupiters" - gas giants, comparable in size and mass to the largest planet in the solar system, but located ten times closer to the parent star.
Because of this, a year on an exoplanet lasts only 1.3 "Earth" days, and its gas shell is heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change threatens lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and Southern France, but now there are fears that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavender began to grow worse due to dry weather and disease-carrying insects; this has caused a constant headache for scientists and farmers who are trying to find a solution.
Eric Sches, an expert at the Provence-based agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM, says: "Lavender in Provence is really under threat, because in recent years this plant has felt the effects of climate change: in spring and especially in autumn, rains have become much less.
This affects the lifespan of lavender.
And then there are the little cicadas, the insects jumping on the leaves, carrying micro-bacteria; in very dry weather, there are a lot of them."
There's a lot at stake.
Lavender not only attracts vacationers; lavender oil is very much in demand in perfumery and cosmetology.
Eric Shes says: "Instead of very long ears with a large number of large flowers, we have small, underdeveloped, weakened or absent altogether.
So we have fewer parts containing essential oil."
Solutions that are now under consideration include improving water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, as well as spraying plants with a protective mixture of clay and water and developing varieties that are more resistant to drought.
