The murder of the journalist underscores that Mexico is becoming increasingly dangerous.
Employees of the weekly newspaper Riodoce usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to cover the latest violent crimes in the state of Sinaloa related to organized crime, corrupt officials or the ongoing war of drug traffickers.
But today, overwhelmed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about security.
They were told they had to change their habits.
Two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: taking the children with them to the office, which in 2009 had already been thrown a grenade, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three words on a blackboard hanging in the room: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column - no evidence is needed, suspicions and internal feelings will be enough.
These are drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being supported by the government or cartels, a whole list of scoundrels, because of which the work of covering the chaos in Mexico becomes dangerous.
Violence has not given respite, and there are more and more journalists among the corpses that are multiplying in the country: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and this year, at least seven people have died in seven states.
Among the latter is their publisher and inspirer, the co-founder of "Riodoce" Javier Valdés Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and be a journalist," Valdez wrote in one of his many books on violent drug-related crimes.
His absence is felt very keenly, although his presence is ubiquitous - a large photograph of Valdés showing his middle finger, with the inscription "Justice" hanging on the facade of the building "Riodos"; two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts that show his smile, face with glasses or his trademark panama.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their common trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although an office of a special federal prosecutor was set up in 2010 to investigate journalistic cases, so far, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, only two cases have been investigated.
As with most of the thousands of murders committed each year related to drug trafficking and organized crime, the killers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
Riodos journalists insist they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are heartbroken, although it is now much more dangerous around them.
Without information about the killers, without justice, talking about security at meetings is of little use," Ibarra said.
"It's very stupid to waste time at this seminar," he says.
"Until we know the cause, we suspect everyone."
On the morning of May 15, Valdés left the Riodos office in the state capital of Culiacana.
He only managed to drive a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot 12 times, probably because of the newspaper's name – which means "Twelfth River".
The shooter drove away in his car and crashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He is survived by his wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually quickly spread through Culiacán.
But almost everyone is silent about Valdez.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the U.S. last January, Sinaloa has become one of the bloodiest battlefields in the country as rival factions struggle to fill the vacuum.
Let's not talk about the fact that every day on the streets of Sinaloa one or more people are killed, or that the cemetery is filled with decorated two-story mausoleums of drug farms, which are larger than the homes of many living people.
Let's forget for a moment that the state of "calm" is simply when one of the cartels takes control of a coastal state with important ports and drug trafficking routes leading to the United States.
Despite this and the fact that Valdés was well aware of the dangers of his job, Ismail Bohorquez, the 60-year-old co-founder and director of Riodos, is crushed by guilt for failing to protect his friend.
He thinks two mistakes helped the murder.
First, an interview was published in February with Damaso López, the leader of one of the cartel's rival factions that is at war with Guzman's sons.
The publication could anger the sons; people who were allegedly members of the gang bought all copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he did not force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper that was writing about the same story was seized.
Valdés was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as the latest milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been evading danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would always be.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroesta and in 2003, along with five colleagues, founded Riodos, selling his $50 shares.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without touching on the topic of drugs," Bohorquez said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation as a bold and honest publication, sales and advertising revenues grew.
Journalists liked that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted that in this publication they could read about what no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after its founding, Riodose received the prestigious Maria Moores Cabo Award for her reporting in Latin America.
That same year, Valdés won the International Press Freedom Award for his courage in investigating drug trafficking in Mexico wherever it went.
He frankly admitted that he was scared.
"I want to move on with my life," he said at the CPJ Awards.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is "a way of life," he said last October in an interview with Rompeviento TV.
"You have to accept the tasks that fall on you as a journalist – either that way or you're just fooling around."
I don't want to be asked, "What did you do when there were so many deaths around... why didn't you say what was going on?"
The employees of Riodos miss Valdés, the prankster who swore like a longshoreman in the port, a friend generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to get together in the living.
They relied on the order he had.
He had to wear his hat at all times.
He had to go to "El Guayabo," the bar opposite the office, and always sit there at the same table.
Now they ask: Was he ruined by the love of the once established order?
His death caused them to question their calculations of how best to do their job and stay alive.
"They don't like it when you understand their wives, their children, their legal business and clandestine drug shipping airfields.
"Those things were over the line," Bohorquez said.
The result, even in the best of times, was a high level of self-censorship and a desire for self-preservation.
You have to believe your instincts.
Stay away from what smells bad.
The problem, says Riodose editor Andres Villareal, is that "the sense of smell can be deceived ... and then what happened to Javier happens."
The old rules, he says and others, no longer apply in Sinaloa — as they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states where there is a toxic mixture of lucrative smuggling routes, weak state institutions and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In the room where Riodos employees had gathered for security training, it was suddenly forbidden to bring cell phones: a few days earlier, it became known that spyware, which is sold exclusively to governments, is used in Mexico to spy on journalists and social activists.
Outside, two police officers take cover in the shade of a tree from the 104-degree heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were tasked by the state government to guard the office of Riodos, which is located in a four-story building in the bourgeois quarter of Culiacana.
Some journalists half-jokingly asked whether these police officers were among the 50 percent of the law enforcement officers about whom the governor himself said that they could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists traveled to a mountainous area that is de facto under the control of drug gangs.
In the next issue, Riodos counted on three main themes.
This is the murder in Sinaloa of the brother of former boxing champion Julio Cesar Chavez.
They also had an exposure of government spending concentrated in the governor's hometown.
And there was a gang kidnapping at one of Culiacán's most expensive restaurants, a block from the prosecutor's office.
It wasn't officially announced who was kidnapped or how it happened, so care had to be taken when it came time to write about what everyone in town knew: that it was a favorite restaurant of both drug dealers and authorities.
One journalist learned from open databases that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which dominated all levels of government for most of the past century.
Recently, several governors from the PRI have faced high-profile allegations of corruption.
Villarreal asked reporters to write about previous incidents at the restaurant, including when the son of "El Chapo" Guzman eluded a military raid.
A few months ago, readers would have searched for Valdez's column with the most reliable information about the kidnapping.
"We would have known what happened before," said Villareal, 46, nicknamed "El Flaco", for his thin physique.
"Today, all channels of communication with our sources are broken."
Valdez's cabinet is now used as a warehouse for posters and stickers protesting the killings of journalists because employees have become what they never thought they would become: activists speaking on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez picked up several posters and went to a demonstration outside the local prosecutor's office the next morning dedicated to another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in the state of Michoacán in the west of the country three days after Valdés was killed.
They found the burned body, and authorities said it was him, based on DNA tests.
Across the country, journalists began to speak louder, organize protests and write "SOS Press" on the sidewalks and walls of houses.
On that day, Director Bohorquez was in Washington, D.C., trying to garner international support in demanding justice in the Valdés case.
In a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after Valdez's murder, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their murders for telling the truth.
After that, she asked not to be given any more assignments to cover the activities of the government, fearing that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdés has said many times that journalists in Mexico are "surrounded" by organized crime, its accomplices in government and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Narco-Journalism, he wrote that it's not just gangs of drug traffickers who kill reporters; they do so on the orders of politicians and security services in cahoots with organized crime.
The Article 19 Press Protection Committee estimates that half of the attacks on journalists last year were ordered by police and government officials.
"In Mexico, you're dying because they want to shut you up," Ramirez says.
Of course, murder terrifies people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
A note was found on her body, presumably written on behalf of the Zetas cartel: "I am here because of my articles."
A computer keyboard and headphones lay next to her severed head.
Some publications chose to shut down, like the newspaper El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua, after her correspondent Miroslava Brich was killed in March.
Others continue to hold on, like "El Magnana" from Nuevo Laredo after the assassination of its leader in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juárez publicly addressed drug cartels through a front-page editorial entitled "What Do You Want from Us?"
Some journalists have left their home states or the country altogether.
It's a painful decision.
It's hard to find work in exile, and they still look out for danger in the streets.
And sometimes they are killed, as apparently happened to photographer Ruben Espinoza, who was murdered in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who stay and continue to work balance risky decisions on a daily basis.
Ibarra – who once dreamed of being a poet – admits that he is afraid to write about the drug trade.
"Mexico is going to hell and that's why I became a journalist," he says.
Last Friday, at midnight, when the last issue was ready for printing, the publishers of Riodoce were sitting on the sidewalk next to the office drinking beer when suddenly their phones rang at the same time.
A series of shootings between rival gangs and security forces near the resort town of Mazatlan left behind, according to confirmed data, 19 corpses.
The war continued to rage, as promised in a series of messages from cartels discovered in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they posted the news on the Riodos website via their mobile phone.
The next day, the first page had to be redone.
Nearby, sirens rang out - another shootout in the vicinity.
Bohorkes looked to see if the police officers guarding them were ready to defend themselves.
If they were scared, they didn't show it.
Sitting under a huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was on display throughout Sinaloa, the Riodos staff continued his work.
"How can you think about shutting down," Bohorquez said, "if on the very day Javier was killed, an intern asked me to send her outside to report?"
Dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it seems like a statue, albeit a terrifying one.
The researchers said that the first remains of an incredible creature the size of a rhino, discovered by a Canadian miner, were preserved so well that experts called it the "Mona Lisa among dinosaurs."
It is so well preserved that they were even able to determine that the color of its scaly skin was reddish-brown – and to say that it had, in a way, a "dark past."
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as "the best preserved of the Thyreophores in the history of the finds and one of the best specimens of a dinosaur in the world."
This fossil is a recently found specimen of Nodosaurus, which lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredibly good condition has stunned researchers who call it "truly remarkable."
This herbivorous thyrophore is the best-preserved fossil of this species in the history of the finds, according to articles in National Geographic magazine.
It was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Suncore Company's Millennium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He stumbled upon something that seemed different from the surrounding rock and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was carried out to find an animal inside an earthen block weighing 2500 feet (1100 kilograms).
Now that all this hard work is done, the finished result can be demonstrated.
"You just have to squint a little, and you can almost believe that he is asleep," said lead author Caleb Brown, a research fellow at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum, where the creation is demonstrated.
"It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved specimens of dinosaurs – the Mona Lisa among dinosaurs."
By studying its skin, the researchers found that this herbivore, despite being covered in a shell and resembling a walking tank, appeared to be exposed to significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerfully shelled dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and applied a protective technique known as protective coloration, which is also used by many animals of our day.
That would allow it to blend in more quickly with its surroundings and avoid encountering enemies, experts say, suggesting it was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old creature, part of the Nodosaurus family, was widely pressed in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and gave it the name Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of museum laboratory assistant Mark Mitchell, one of the members of the group who spent more than 7,000 hours on its painstaking excavation.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and shell plates on his body.
They found a protective coloration, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although protective coloration is well spread, the discovery came as a surprise because the size of the dinosaur Borealopelta far exceeds the size of living animals with protective coloration.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred the disguise of confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with protective coloration – for example, deer, zebras or armadillos – are much smaller and are more accessible prey, which indicates that Nodosaurus had to seriously struggle for survival.
"The serious threat from predators to the massive, powerfully shelled dinosaur shows how dangerous the predatory dinosaurs of the Cretaceous period were," Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in the dinosaur's scales also suggests that its skin must have been reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about its life, including the preserved contents of its digestive tract, to find out what it ate during its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was carried away into the sea, where it sank and lay back down to the bottom of the ocean.
In those days, Alberta was as warm as it is now in South Florida, and rivers and oceans were likely to extend much further inland than they are now.
"This Nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, and at the same time completely preserved in three dimensions, retaining the original shape of the animal," brown said.
"As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it looked then, in the Early Cretaceous period.
You don't have to resort to imagination to recreate it, you just have to squint slightly, and you can almost believe that he is asleep. "
The Cretaceous period is the era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of these, the Tyrannosaurus Rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, the thyreophore could have been hunted by one of its formidable ancestors.
These include acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot-long (11.5-meter)-long monster weighing six tons.
Scientists whose latest discoveries are published in the journal Modern Biology believe that Borealopelta was carried away to sea after death and mummified in silt.
The creature was found by Sean Funk when he was working at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to museum staff, it is the best-preserved thyreophore in the world, along with skin and shell, and it is intact, from the muzzle to the femur bones.
On average, these creatures reached about 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3000 pounds (1300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spikes protruding from the shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivorous thyreophore stepped heavily on what is now Canada, until a flooded river carried it into the open sea.
But the underwater burial of the dinosaur preserved its shell with accuracy to the smallest detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin still cover the bumpy shell plates along the dinosaur skull.
As Michael Greshko wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, such a degree of preservation is "rare as winning the lottery."
The longer I look at it, the more striking it seems.
Fossilized remains of the skin still cover the bumpy armored plates that dot the animal's skull.
His right front leg is elongated along the side, five fingers on it are turned upwards.
I can count the scales on its sole."
