How did one activist find out the answer to the question "Whose streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to the core.
Just a day after arriving in New York city as part of a tourist trip, the St. Louis native was sitting on a bed in an apartment rented through Airbnb, scrolling through the Facebook feed on her phone.
She came across a post from a high school.
It said: "Police have just killed an eighteen-year-old child and he is still lying in the middle of the street."
Noticing that no one else in her feed posted this information, puzzled, she shut down Facebook and opened Twitter.
In her feed there were many reposts of a user with the nickname @TheePharoah.
A rapper from Greater St. Louis tweeted the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed, eighteen-year-old black boy killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's lifeless body spread out in the middle of the street where it would stay for four hours.
"It's wild," Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her circle.
She put down her phone and later in the evening returned to tweets about people gathering at Canfield Drive.
There were photos of a signal tape and screaming people and a man claiming to be Brown's father holding a poster saying, "A Ferguson cop just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live broadcast of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another policeman, she said, cocked the trigger of his rifle and yelled, "I'm going to kill you all... animals!"
"It's not a standard situation," Ferrell said at the time.
"This is not the same murder as the ones to which we are accustomed and which we can call typical.
At that moment, I felt chills.
I was angry and crying."
She took a ticket for the return flight and flew home the next day.
Landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided they would both head to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next nearly three years was the subject of a new documentary, "Whose Streets?" that will be released on August 11.
It's a tale of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience from the perspective of the people living in the community and filling the streets demanding answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter dressed in a floral dress and a wreath to match the color, they recalled a conversation they had had had had before this morning countless times "about the experiences of blacks and their situation."
She recalls saying, "Remember how I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed?
We're going to Ferguson now because a police officer killed an eighteen-year-old boy and it was wrong."
"I couldn't help but take her," Ferrell said later.
"What is happening today is the culmination of ... what happened before.
She needs to know about it, see it, and be educated on it.
She must not only be well-versed in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of black experience and their positions and what we must do to become free, to be free.
Even if I manage to provide her with an environment in which she personally does not face obvious racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would have done her a disservice if I had shielded her from that."
When they arrived in Ferguson, they made their first stop at South Florissant Road, a site across the street from the police station, which had become something of a tent camp, while activists waited for reports of officer Darren Wilson's final non-indictment.
There, Ferrell and his daughter joined a local entrepreneur who was preparing lunch packages.
They collected packages and helped distribute them to protesters.
Little by little, a new type of activism took shape in Ferrell's mind.
"My activism has completely changed since Aug. 9," she said, noting that as a student at Missouri-St. Louis University, she was president of the Association of Minority Health Students and worked on food equity and health inequalities among black communities.
"I had no experience as an organizer.
It came by itself."
A few weeks later, at an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Sabaa Folayan, one of her co-directors.
Folayan said she and her chief cinematographer, Lucas Alvarado-Farrer, "just wanted to document" the events.
Ferrell came up with the question, "Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story to play on?"
This skepticism was inspired by numerous people, often white, who came to the community to capitalize on its pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We've heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson don't get the spotlight, and wanted to do it differently."
Folayan had already teamed up with her co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism on death row.
His involvement sparked sympathy for the project in Ferrell and six other locals with whom the "Whose Streets?" team had been in touch in the years since Brown's murder.
"In this documentary, it's not someone speaking for us or with us, it's us talking," Davis said.
"That was the most important thing to me how these people would be represented, because that's how I'm going to be represented."
And while the goal of the project was not to focus on Ferrell's experience at all — in an effort to show that the movement "is not about a leader-savior, but about how the community comes together," as Folayan said — she was the most open of the film's participants.
As a result, "Whose Streets?" shows unexpectedly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, such as how she fell in love and married her wife.
"I felt naked," Ferrell said, laughingly about the first time she saw the finished product.
"But I understood that when you do this kind of work and humanize black people, there has to be some level of vulnerability."
In addition, Ferrell's story again discusses and emphasizes the role of the black homosexual woman in the broader context of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement's three founders — those who created the #BlackLivesMatter tag on social media after the murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 — identify as homosexual.
"Black gay women in leadership positions support this whole movement," Ferrell says. - And all because we are constantly fighting on several fronts.
Black gay women have to bear all this burden."
Folayan agreed, noting that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a host of gay black women."
However, she insists that "this is not a case of positive discrimination", and that Ferrell was not chosen as the central character of the film because of her distinctive features.
"She was the person who awakened that energy," she said.
"On the other hand, it's not a coincidence that she's come to the fore because when"
You can feel her energy through the screen."
Meanwhile, Ferguson has long since no movie cameras, but complex racial ties between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell will be on probation for another two and a half years for blocking the highway during the demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the place she calls home simply: "A mess."
She still holds on to the speech she learned when she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
We must fight for our freedom.
We have to win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains."
