The emergence of similarities: the artist creates portraits using the DNA of Chelsea Manning
In the center of the hall at the Friedman Gallery in New York, people's faces hang from the ceiling on a wire - white, black and brown, all somehow subtly similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harbourg from cheek strokes and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent clippings from Fort Levenworth Prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for famously transmitting confidential diplomatic cables on the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called "The Emergence of Similarities."
It's the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and famous dissident whom Barack Obama commuted just three days before the end of his presidency.
By analyzing the DNA obtained from Manning with a computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of faces that people with such a genome might have, Dewey-Harbourg created a profound, if difficult to understand, manifesto devoted not only to the plasticity of DNA data - the various ways of interpreting them and the inherent determinism of these interpretations - but also the concept of identity.
Manning, who was born with the name Bradley Edward but has openly said since she was a teenager that she considered herself a woman, was sentenced to 20 counts in 2013, including six Espionage Act violations, computer fraud and theft.
Photos of her in prison were not available, so only one photo of her was known: a grainy black-and-white selfie in which Manning, in a platinum-shaded wig, clearly feeling awkward, sits behind the wheel of a car; she became associated with this photograph.
In 2015, Dewey-Harbourg completed her 2012 project Visions of Strangers with great success.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people with the help of forensic evidence such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, extracting DNA from this garbage and creating images of what these people could look like.
And then she got an email from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some kind of portrait to illustrate the article," Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview screening of the new exhibition to the press.
At the time, Chelsea couldn't be visited or photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait made from her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became pen pals and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book, "Depressed Images," illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, who depicted how in the future the president would mitigate Chelsea's punishment and she would be able to visit the exhibition in person.
That Obama did decide to release Manning just days after the book was published came as a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a military prison in Kansas.
There's something profound and powerful about the fact that the exhibit opens right now that Donald Trump is declaring war on people who disclose classified information in the government and inventing new ways to foment the hatred on Twitter that he is designed to soften.
When Dewey-Harbourg was asked about the coincidence of all this time, she said that "nothing happens by chance."
In the artist's statement written on the wall of the gallery, Manning's huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of an i in her last name) calls for an end to "automatic separation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture."
On the opposite side is its mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of pencil-drawn C, G, and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist scientifically exquisitely puts it), Dewey-Harbourg hoped to show how we are all remarkably similar, at least in our biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome doesn't determine what we are, how open the genetic data is to interpretation, and how subjective it is," Dewey-Harbourg said. her 2007 video work False Memories is also featured here.
"DNA data can tell us so many different stories, and 30 of those stories are here."
The last part of the exhibition, which fits in one room, is the aforementioned novel in the comics.
In it, King Kong-style Manning appears above the U.S. Correctional Barracks building with a loudspeaker in his hand.
"If they kill your speech, they will win," it reads.
"So never shut up."
"This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me," says the artist, who greets us from Philadelphia.
"I still get goosebumps when I talk about it."
Manning has yet to see the exhibit in person — as was presciently portrayed in the comics — but when she arrives, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacra gathered like crowds of protesters.
This is also done intentionally, like everything in the exhibition up to the height (5"2, Manning's height), on which genetic haplogroups were drawn with a pencil.
"I used to hang them on the walls, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people," Dewey-Harbourg says of the portraits.
"I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea, as a movement that was behind her release. "
