Startups that will help your company not to become another Uber
Aimee Errett wanted to gauge the level of satisfaction among her e-commerce startup's employees, but the surveys didn't work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or worse, disingenuous.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
"It's never been consistent and objective," said Errett, who runs 75-person company Madison Reed, a San Francisco-based company that e-commerces hair cares.
So she turned to third parties for help.
Now there is a new kind of startups in the field of working with personnel, which help companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure employee engagement, they allow companies to conduct rapid surveys, reach out to specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and contact the directorate directly.
"We now have tools like Strava and Fitbit to monitor health, and where is Fitbit for your company?" says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City-based startup Glint, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she has gained a greater understanding of what her employees are thinking and feeling in three years of using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a heat map of the company and shows in a visual form which departments have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies are slowly realizing that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become the next Uber, which was involved in the scandal when a former employee published a blog post in which he described an aggressive environment in which those who expressed discontent were punished.
For startups like Glint, it's a desire to control the situation – an opportunity for profitable business.
Let's Talk About Payment, an online portal dedicated to financial technology, estimates that the global governance, regulatory and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid Uber's declining reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber appeared among the clients.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to submit custom-made employee opinion polls, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if a top manager is affected, complaints go directly to the directorate.
"The public opinion court has seized power from the inspectors," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If a company finds itself mistreating employees or behaving unethically, even if inspectors don't intervene, the company could face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by customers, employee churn and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, has used Convercent for more than a year to make sure employees are up to date with policies and procedures and to offer an easy way to contact the company's head office.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look up the phone number or email of the head office, file a formal complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, head of legal at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, problems that used to be hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay – can be more quickly detected and addressed.
"I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of employees' situations," said Vitrano, who leads the Ruby Tuesday network's risk management team.
"And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees."
According to Quinland, companies began to take ethics, values and employee engagement more seriously in 2002, after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron Case.
But it wasn't until "social media gained mass adoption" that companies realized they couldn't keep their dirty laundry from spreading virally online.
"Before they started using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for using their products.
It's a business model and opportunity that has been endorsed by venture capitalists who have backed both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising when you consider the interconnected nature of companies, culture, and venture capital.
A growing body of research demonstrates that today's employees expect more from their jobs than they did before.
In highly competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects are just the bare minimum.
Employees want to feel accepted and appreciated, and that they are dedicating their time to a company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to work for a company, feel that they are being heard, and that the work they do is paying off, they try harder to make that company a success," said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, which employs both Convercent and Glint.
Investors earn income when companies in their portfolio are doing well; companies are doing well when employees are dedicated and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, then it's no surprise that they find support.
According to workplace culture experts, it is important to have data on employee engagement.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can give the impression that change is coming.
And if change doesn't come quickly enough, or doesn't come at all, frustration can develop and employees lose interest.
"If you're going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you have to be willing to have 4,000 conversations," says Russell Rath, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
"Because if you don't go all the way, employees will be guessing, 'Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care?"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day someone reports a problem using Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long term this knowledge will help it to retain employees more effectively in an industry known for high turnover.
"If you don't try to create a culture of transparency, you're going to lose people," Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
