Create a comic book novel: One Castle in English History
In the recent past, the tiny Scotney Castle was filmed in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 70s and 80s served as a haven for Margaret Thatcher.
But for 700 years, from his cozy place in the Bule River Valley in Kent, he watched the turbulent history around him, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman with a spear hair and a penchant for historical documents, for a comic book novel.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he says enthusiastically.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand."
"The Castle in England" covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells about the families who lived in Scotch; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Bryonie May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabelle Greenberg.
This is not the first book by Rhodes to be based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote Teeth of a Dead Man and Other Stories, a collection of British Library documents; this project suddenly touched him to the core.
"I could have been touched simply by the fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites," he says.
"It's his fingerprint"
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days a fire was lit for lighting.
And 300 years from now, in the future, you feel like you're there too.
Oh, how I love archives!"
For a man gripped by such a passion for old papers, getting support from the National Trust and the English Art Council and living in a castle for four months ("Honestly, I got a little late there") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days studying the "new" Victorian castle, going through the archives and looking at the numerous treasures of the estate and antiques - for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that had lain in the moat for centuries.
He walked around the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to foresters, gardeners and sometimes with artists working on illustrations for his book.
Then at night he would "drink whiskey and sit down to write."
The history of Scotney Castle is not well studied because the National Trust only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff were just beginning to deal with the archive, which he describes as "what aristocrats have been dumping in the attic for centuries."
Diaries, letters from british times, maps showing who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring," rhodes says, "but two families fought for this birch tree.
It happens, folks!"
In some of the collection's stories, the castle becomes the starting point for broader explorations in English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasants' Revolution of 1381.
"There are accounts of a revolt that took place at the castle in 1380 in a book called The Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex," Rhodes says.
"The peasant uprising started in these places, and I thought the revolt was the right start.
Maybe they were related?"
Other subjects are strongly connected with the history of the castle - for example, "The Priest", which tells about the Jesuit priest, whom the Darrel family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "The Smuggler," about the eighteenth-century smuggler Arthur Durrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by stuffing the coffin with stones (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrels are Rhodes' favorite family of all that the Scottish people inhabited: "Gentlemen seem to have been a perfect crook, forever going into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy older women – I imagine them as a company of pretty guys who know how to care for the heiresses of large fortunes. "
After finishing his work at the castle, Rhodes looks for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Eljamänmäki - a place where at the beginning of the XX century there was a sanatorium, and then it was again overgrown with forest.
But Scottish remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
"I felt something like this: damn, I need to go back to real life."
