The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly at his instigation, regional merchants received state orders for kickbacks, but did not fulfill their obligations to clean the separated parts of launch vehicles in the Arkhangelsk region and the Komi Republic.
In 2012, a jury found him not guilty.
The responsibilities assigned to him in TsENKI for technological development extended to various projects, but the main one was the construction of a cosmodrome in the Far East.
Oleg Ostapenko, who was then the head of the Federal Space Agency, in an interview with Kommersant, directly said that the state of affairs in Vostochny "was critical already in October 2013."
The fact is that a strategic mistake was made during the planning: the completion of construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 launch vehicle were scheduled for the same time - the end of 2015.
In order to carry out the launch before the end of the year, it was decided to complete the construction six months earlier and the deadlines were shifted from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process, it was necessary to go on a trick: TsENKI specialists began to conduct parallel installation of technological equipment at unfinished facilities.
The main supporter of this idea was Andrei Okhlopkov.
Despite the existing risks and the postponement that still happened (instead of December 2015, the Soyuz flew away only on April 28, 2016), this idea justified itself, says a Kommersant source at the cosmodrome: "Otherwise, we would not have carried out a single launch from Vostochny, but would have been engaged in construction."
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversees the creation of the cosmodrome, jokingly called Andrei Okhlopkov his "space Susanin", but it was from him that he almost always asked for information about the progress of construction.
Mr. Okhlopkov was also remembered for his directness: for example, in an interview with Kommersant, he proposed to deprive the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Spetsstroy) of the status of the only executor in Vostochny and work directly with subcontractors: "Why should we put all our eggs in one basket of Spetsstroy?"
This idea was supported by the government.
Since 2017, TsENKI has assumed the duties of the general contractor in order to complete the construction and installation works at the launch and technical complex by the planned fourth quarter.
According to Kommersant, the reason for the transition of Mr. Okhlopkov to a new place of work was disagreements with the leadership of TsENKI regarding the ways to complete the construction of structures and complexes of the cosmodrome, as well as methods of working with subcontractors.
"It was decided that this would be better for everyone," says one of the top managers involved in the construction of vostochny.
An employee of the government apparatus, in turn, calls the decision strange: "He was one of the best specialists, it will not be easy to find an equivalent replacement for him."
According to Kommersant, this will not be required: the post of technical director of the cosmodrome will be abolished, and its functions will be scattered among the units of TsENKI.
