Red meat, dairy, and chocolate can help relieve IBD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered to be a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies suggest otherwise: A diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products may help relieve symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects an estimated 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to alleviate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington found that the main amino acid of the protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the gut make sure that harmful microbes coming from food do not enter the body.
Cells that can trigger the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body and at the same time not harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much disturbed in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacterium in their gut develop tolerance-boosting cells.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan - one of the building blocks of protein - to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one species of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of tolerance-boosting cells.
The more tryptophan the mice had, the more of these immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet may promote a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Luiza Cervantes-Barraghanvas, studying a variety of immune cells that increase tolerance, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same lineage, but was kept separately, did not have them.
She hypothesized that the difference could be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice — communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the mice's gut cells were sequenced, and six species of bacteria were found present in mice that had immune cells but were absent in mice that did not have them.
Mice raised in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this kind of immune cells received L. reuteri, and immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how the bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of the liquid — without the bacteria — to underdeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have turned into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan processing, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells also dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragán explains that humans have the same tolerance-boosting cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the byproducts of tryptophan from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel disease, defects in genes associated with tryptophan have been found.
She says: "Perhaps we need to strengthen the development of these cells, because the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri could potentially lead to an expansion of their population."
