Props for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House's decision last month to drive a Marine corps helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-and-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One" with the president on board, was the centerpiece of a July 17 White House event that showcased U.S. construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and top White House officials inspected technology products from all fifty states.
The helicopter, manufactured in Connecticut, was stationed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift truck from Mississippi.
According to records from the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the department responsible for operating the helicopter, the White House Military Office ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO," just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of the "unusual" event.
"I just wanted you to make sure you were aware because this is an unusually widely publicized event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Marine Corps First Deputy Chief of Aviation, on the eve of the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with restrictions on hours of operation.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records obtained by TIME magazine, it remains unclear whether a second crew was eventually required.
Hatch's Law prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event contradicts this ruling.
"Among other things, we asked if this was a violation of Hatch's Law, and we were told that it was not," the commander wrote.
"It looks like you have nowhere to go," the deputy chief replied.
The "Made in America" event was declared an official event by the White House and was not covered by Hatch's Law.
But even official events have a political touch.
During the event, the president made efforts to advance health care reform, then in the Senate, and touted attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as "Marine One" and "Air Force One" for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are instructed to use them for travel.
But requesting them solely in the interest of photo capability is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of discussion in February, when a presidential plane drove in the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was inundated with messages complaining about his predecessor's use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is thrilled with the 'Made in America' show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," said White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsey Walters.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and on the South Lawn to train the transportation of the President of the United States to the White House with an inch accuracy.
When Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings outside the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight performed for the "Made in America" event was credited to the crew against the necessary training flights for the month.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of "non-presidential support tasks."
According to the White House, taxpayers did not bear the cost of any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of the company "Sikorsky" said that the company did not take part in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep records of the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the Department of Defense's hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense's reimbursement rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per hour of flight.
The unit's records record the aerial vehicle's time in the air was 30 minutes each way from its airfield at Marine Corps Air Base Quantico in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this rate.
"Calculating the cost to taxpayers based on an estimated reimbursement rate is completely flawed," Walters says.
"These approximate rates include personnel, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in annual appropriations."
According to a 2015 study by RAND Corporation, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and expenses specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer was advocating the use of a helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to showcase things made in America this week," Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I assume, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
So, of course, it's entirely appropriate to pay attention to that."
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he definitely sat in the driver's seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump reached out to Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of the company's products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said. "I have three."
