Electricity is becoming cheaper for both residents and producers of Buryatia
The decades-long efforts of the Soviet and post-Soviet authorities of the Republic of Buryatia (Eastern Siberia) to establish fair tariffs for electricity consumers are beginning to bear fruit.
From September 1, the cost of low-voltage electricity for industrial recipients will be reduced by 25%.
The Federal Antimonopoly Service of the country in accordance with the Decree of the Government of the Russian Federation "On Amendments to the Rules of the Wholesale Market of Electric Energy and Capacity and to the Consolidated Forecast Balance of Production and Supply of Electric Energy (Capacity) within the Unified Energy System of Russia by Subjects of the Russian Federation" (dated 17.07.2017 No. 842) established indicative prices for electricity and capacity for industrial consumers of the Republic of Buryatia.
As a result, the cost of electricity for Buryat producers is reduced by a quarter, which will greatly facilitate the life of small and medium-sized enterprises and individual entrepreneurs.
For many decades, the republic's leaders have been circling the thresholds of Moscow offices in futile attempts to equalize the region in tariffs with the neighboring Irkutsk region with a cascade of hydroelectric power plants on the Angara River flowing from Lake Baikal, the main catchment area for which is Buryatia.
And only this year the movement began.
In March, tariffs for electricity for the population of the republic were reduced from 4.24 rubles / kWh to 3.93 rubles / kWh, or by 7.3%.
With the inclusion of Buryatia by the decision of the federal government in the List of territories of price zones of the wholesale market, for which the features of the functioning of the wholesale and retail markets are established, it is the turn of industrial consumers.
According to analysts, this is only the beginning, since the population of the Irkutsk region pays 1.01 rubles per kilowatt / hour.
But no one dares to name at least an approximate date for new tariff shifts downwards for Buryatia.
