The National Union of Unskilled, Municipal and Boiler Workers (GMB) is concerned about the investment in McVitie's factory in Glasgow
The union is seeking guarantees from managers of biscuit maker McVitie's due to its long-term commitment to production at the Glasgow plant.
The Scottish branch of GMB reports that the company was silent on the issue of future investments at the Tolkros facility.
The factory, which produces Hobnobs and Rich Tea biscuits, among other products, employs more than 500 people.
Pladis, owner of McVitie's, says it has invested more than £5 million in the property over the past few years.
The company adds that in the event of any changes in the operation of the facility, employees and union representatives "will be the first to know about them."
In a letter to the head of the company's facility, gmb's Scottish branch demanded mcVitie's response to concerns that funding would not be used to upgrade production lines.
Senior organiser Drew Duffy said: "Members of our union are deeply concerned that we cannot get clarity from the facility's general manager on the needs of the business and investment plan for the future of Tolkross. "
Families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is high in the local community and in greater Glasgow; it is an essential pillar of decent work in an area of high unemployment and social deprivation.
So, in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising living wages and chronic decline in manufacturing, the East End of Glasgow desperately needs production to flourish at McVitie's factory.
According to a Pladis spokesperson, "The manager of the Tolkros facility only yesterday received a letter from the Scottish branch of GMB, and the company will respond immediately, as we appreciate our continued cooperation with employees and union representatives."
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting with GMB employees and representatives in Tolkross to openly discuss a number of issues.
We spoke to employees about how, like all companies operating in the most competitive and volatile economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our actions – and this applies to all our facilities and activities – in order to remain competitive.
"In recent years, we have invested more than £5 million in our Tolkros facility, particularly in production lines and performance improvements."
We are fully aware of the value of Tolkross as a production facility, and in the event of any change in the work at this facility, employees and union representatives will be the first to know about it."
Putin said that the authorities will not give instructions to Rosneft and Gazprom
Vladimir Putin said that the Kremlin and the Cabinet of Ministers should get involved in the issue of gas supplies to the Eastern Petrochemical Company (VNHK), but no one will give instructions to Gazprom, like Rosneft.
So Russian President Vladimir Putin responded to the request of Igor Sechin to assist in resolving the contradictions that have arisen.
The head of state drew attention to the fact that relations between Rosneft and Gazprom should be resolved exclusively on the basis of market principles.
Earlier, the head of Rosneft, Igor Sechin, at a meeting on the implementation of major investment projects in the Far Eastern Federal District, said that the lack of an agreement with Gazprom on gas for VNHK jeopardizes the project implementation period.
Sechin noted that the dialogue with Gazprom on this issue continues.
Gazprom offers to find gas resources from the perimeter of Rosneft, but we do not have such resources," Sechin added.
Recall that Rosneft asked to be allowed to use for the Eastern Petrochemical Company gas from the Kirinskoye field of Gazprom, located on the shelf of Sakhalin.
In June, Gazprom said that negotiations on this issue were continuing, and "there are no sharp corners there."
Did PSG warn Barcelona about Neymar's transfer three years ago?
A La Liga participant may regret his interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain won't stop stalking Neymar after the club offered £189 million for his ransom, but did they warn Barcelona about the world-record raid three years ago?
The sensational offer has revived the summer transfer window as the Ligue 1 club was poised to break the world record for the cost of a move, more than double the previous mark linked to Paul Pogba's return to Manchester United last season for £89 million.
When the transfer is complete, Neymar will become the most expensive player in the world, as well as the highest paid professional athlete in the world, as PSG offer him a salary of more than £500,000 a week net.
Barcelona are known to be furious with the way the offer was made and how Neymar terminated his contract, despite the fact that, as a source close to the Catalan club's management insists, the club has always done everything possible for the player since his transfer from Santos in 2013.
But wasn't the football world warned of such a possibility three years ago by the PSG president?
When Manchester City expressed interest in hiring Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al Khelaifi issued a stern warning to any club that wanted to lure one of PSG's best players.
"I'm not worried because they know that if they touch one of our players, then we will turn against them, we will make offers to their players," Al-Khelaifi said.
"We treat all clubs with respect.
But if they try to recruit one of our players, they will face consequences."
Barcelona appear to have crossed that line when the Spanish club earlier this summer expressed interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti.
PSG have made it clear that they will not let go of the Italian national team player on any terms, and now it is likely that Barcelona are feeling the consequences of their offer in the form of the loss of one of their most valuable players, Neymar.
